recordings.rmk: Although the main subject is a calling male Cuckoo, the clip also contains a burst of Skylark song. The Skylark was singing before the Cuckoo started and had the good grace to stop and let the Cuckoo dominate the airwaves, before recommencing its own outpouring. No editing was carried out on the clip. The timings could not have been improved by a conductor!

Calls from a male Cuckoo that, over the course of several mornings, sang from the same hillside. During its broadcast period, it flew a few times - but only a matter of metres from a post to a rock (and then, later, back to the post). The clip records the bird moving. Because the recorder was nearer the post, the volume increases. Roughly in the middle of the clip, some 'choking gurgles' are recorded. These are at 0:28 (two calls) and, the clearer of the two examples, 0:33. Because I left the recorder and retreated, I did not see if the gurgles were made in flight or, as I think more likely, upon landing. Later recordings, made when it was definitely perched, also contain a few gurgling notes.
